documentation:
Assets is the core Dogen meta-model representing software entities.

@section assets_0 Overview

Assets is a meta-model that strives to provide a technical-space agnostic
type representation, designed for code generation. Injection models
are obtained via frontends and transformed into "bare" asset models, at
which point they can enter its pipeline. Within it, they are processed
until they form a cohesive whole. They are then in a suitable state for
code generation.

@section asset_1 Mission

The objectives of the assets model are:

@li to represent all high-level entities that exist across a number
of technical spaces used in software engineering. These entities
are not necessarily limited to programming entities, though, of course,
these form the core set of elements we're interested in. Additional
entities such as build sytems and high-level patterns such as GoF
and others are also captured.

@li to provide the tooling required to combine multiple models
together into a bigger model - called the @e merged model.

@li to ensure the consistency of the merged model via validation
rules (such as verifying that all types have a definitions,
etc.).

elements.name: meta_model::attribute
elements.documentation: Represents an attribute in an object.

attributes.name: unparsed_type
attributes.documentation:
Original type name as it appeared in the source, without any parsing.

Name must be in one of the supported notations.

attributes.name: parsed_type
attributes.documentation: Tree of names that represent the type of the attribute, after suitable parsing.

attributes.name: is_immutable
attributes.documentation: If true, the attribute can only be read but not set.

attributes.name: is_fluent
attributes.documentation: If true, the attribute's setter will return the object iteself.

attributes.name: member_variable_name
attributes.documentation:
Representation of the attribute name as a member variable.

Note that at present we only support a single style for naming member variables,
across all languages. This will have to be revisited in the future.

attributes.name: getter_setter_name
attributes.documentation: Name to use for getter and setter.

elements.name: meta_model::name_tree
elements.documentation:
Adds support for name composition as a tree-like structure.

A name tree has the responsibility of representing an instantiation of a generic
type with all of its type parameters, which themselves can also be generic types
and so on. It may also represent the simpler case of a non-generic type, in which
case only the parent name is populated and there are no children.

attributes.name: current
attributes.documentation: Name for the current level of the tree.

attributes.name: children
attributes.documentation: Names of the child elements.

attributes.name: are_children_opaque
attributes.documentation:
If true, the association with its children can be opaque.

Children are considered opaque when the parent does not require knowledge
about the childs' internal structure. This is the case, for example, with C and
C++ pointers, references and so on.

attributes.name: is_circular_dependency
attributes.documentation: If true, the presence of the current name causes a circular dependency.

attributes.name: is_current_simple_type
attributes.documentation: Returns true if @e current is a simple type such as a built-in or an enumeration.

attributes.name: is_floating_point
attributes.documentation: If true, "current" stores a floating point type.

elements.documentation: Ability to have a name.

attributes.name: name

elements.name: meta_model::Documentable

attributes.name: documentation

Code comments.

These are expected to follow the grammar of the comment processing tools
of the technical space in question, e.g. Doxygen for C++, JavaDoc for Java,
etc.

attributes.name: meta_name
attributes.documentation: Name of the element in the meta-model that this instance conforms to.

attributes.name: intrinsic_technical_space
attributes.documentation:
Describes the intrinsic nature of the modeling element with regards to technical
spaces.

If the element can be mapped to a technical space then its intrinsic nature is
agnostic. Otherwise, the element belongs to a concrete technical space.

elements.name: meta_model::Configurable
elements.documentation: Ability to have meta-data associated.

attributes.name: configuration
attributes.documentation: Configuration for this element.

elements.name: meta_model::Element
elements.documentation:
A unit of coding that can be code generated.

We define the Element object template purely to make our life easier
when creating the element class. It is not required for any other
purpose.

elements.name: meta_model::name
elements.documentation:
Name of an element in asset space.

A name represents a point in asset space, and this point can only be
used by one asset element. Names can be uniquely identified by their
qualified ID.

Name has the following properties: a) two different points in element space
cannot have the same name and b) the same point in element space can only
have one and only one name.

Names are required in addition to just using the qualfied ID representation
because we use them to infer all sorts of properties for an element (namespaces,
naming files, etc).

attributes.name: simple
attributes.documentation:
Simple (non-qualified) name of the assets element at this address.

The simple name must be unique for a given location.

attributes.name: location
attributes.documentation: Where the name is located in element space.

elements.name: meta_model::origin_types
elements.documentation: What originated the model element.

attributes.name: target
attributes.documentation: The element is part of the target model.

attributes.name: proxy_reference
attributes.documentation:
The element was part of a reference model which is a proxy model.

Proxy models expose types from existing code such as STL, boost, etc,
providing a way to expose third party code into Dogen so that we
can make use of these types.

attributes.name: non_proxy_reference
attributes.documentation: The element was part of a reference model which is regular dogen model.

attributes.name: not_yet_determined
attributes.documentation: The origin of the element is not yet known

elements.name: meta_model::Stateful
elements.documentation: Ability to have a state.

attributes.name: all_attributes
local_attributes
attributes.documentation: The set of all attributes directly associated with the type.

attributes.name: inherited_attributes
attributes.documentation:
The set of all attributes obtained via inheritance, by parent name.

Note that we are using name as a key by design (instead of id); it is required for
formatting.

attributes.name: is_immutable
attributes.documentation: If true, do not generate setters for the element's attributes.

attributes.name: is_fluent
attributes.documentation: If true, generate fluent setters.

elements.name: meta_model::location
elements.documentation:
Identifies a hierarchy of containment within the asset space.

Elements exist at unique points within the asset space called @e
addresses.  However, certain elements have the ability to contain
other elements, creating in effect new dimensions in assets space. The
location class keeps track of these dimensions. Note that the
attributes of this class are hierarchical, i.e.  external modules
contain model modules and so forth. These attributes are best thought
of as a single linked list, where segments of that linked list have
different meaning. However, because we care about these meanings, we
implemented the type with a number of linked lists, one per meaning.

A location is not necessarily connected to modules, although these are
the main model elements that provide containment. For example, inner
classes are contained within classes; in assets terms it means a
location should also have an "object" attribute to represent this
relationship.

Also, note that the location class itself encodes the address of the
element that owns that location; returning to the linked list idea,
the tail of the linked list is the name of the element, and the
remaining linked list provides the location of the element.

attributes.name: external_modules
attributes.documentation:
All modules external to the model itself.

It is sometimes useful to create a model within a set of existing
modules. In this case, the model does not own the existing modules and
they are considered "external" to the model. This is useful, for
example, when declaring a model within a larger project such as @e
dogen::assets. In this case, @e dogen is the external module.

attributes.name: model_modules
internal_modules
attributes.documentation: Sub-modules within a model.

attributes.name: element
attributes.documentation:
Name of the owning element, if any.

For coding elements which are located within other assets elements
that are not modules, such as attributes, inner classes, etc.

elements.name: meta_model::element
elements.documentation:
Represents a generic assets construct.

An element is anything of interest in a problem domain which needs to be
expressed in code generation. It covers both types (objects, enumerations, etc),
meta-types (object templates) and non-types (modules and backend specific entities).

attributes.name: decoration
attributes.documentation: If set, decoration to be added to each generated file.

elements.name: meta_model::model
elements.documentation: Intermediate representation of a masd model.

attributes.name: references
attributes.documentation:
All other intermediate models that this model depends on, mapped to their
origin.

attributes.name: leaves
attributes.documentation:
All leaf types in this model.

Leaves are types concrete types which have a parent.

attributes.name: input_technical_space
attributes.documentation: Technical space in which this model was written.

attributes.name: output_technical_spaces
attributes.documentation: Technical spaces into which to extract the final model.

attributes.name: structural_elements
attributes.documentation: All structural elements in this model.

attributes.name: decoration_elements
attributes.documentation: All decoration elements in this model.

attributes.name: variability_elements
attributes.documentation: All variability elements in this model.

attributes.name: mapping_elements
attributes.documentation: Model elements related to element mapping.

attributes.name: templating_elements
attributes.documentation: Elements related to text templates.

attributes.name: serialization_elements
attributes.documentation: Elements related to serialization.

elements.name: meta_model::Visitable
elements.documentation: The ability to handle visitation.

attributes.name: base_visitor
attributes.documentation: Base class of the visitor that visits the current element, if any.

attributes.name: derived_visitor
attributes.documentation: Derived class of the visitor that visits the current element, if any.

elements.name: meta_model::Associatable
elements.documentation: The element has the ability to associate itself with other elements.

attributes.name: transparent_associations
attributes.documentation: Elements that are involved in aggregation or composition relationships.

attributes.name: opaque_associations
attributes.documentation:
Elements that are involved in aggregation or composition relationships via
indirection.

This is used to break cycles where required.

attributes.name: associative_container_keys
attributes.documentation: Elements that are keys in an associative container.

elements.name: meta_model::Generalizable
elements.documentation: The element has the ability to be part of a generalization relationship.

attributes.name: is_parent
attributes.documentation: True if this element is the parent of one or more elements, false otherwise.

attributes.name: is_child
attributes.documentation: If true, the element has at least one parent.

attributes.name: is_leaf
attributes.documentation: True if the type has a parent but no children.

attributes.name: is_final
attributes.documentation: If true, the element cannot be inherited from.

attributes.name: is_final_requested
attributes.documentation:
If present and true/false, user has requested is_final to be true/false.

If not present, user did not make any statements with regards to finality.

attributes.name: is_abstract
attributes.documentation: If true, the type is an abstract type.

attributes.name: in_inheritance_relationship
attributes.documentation: True if the object is related to at least one other object as a parent or a child.

attributes.name: root_parents
attributes.documentation: Top-most parents at the root of the inheritance hierarchy, if any.

attributes.name: parents
attributes.documentation: Direct parent of this element, if any.

attributes.name: leaves
attributes.documentation: Elements that are at the bottom of the inheritance tree.

elements.name: meta_model::Relatable
elements.documentation: Element has the ability to have relationships with other elements.

elements.name: meta_model::technical_space
elements.documentation: Models need to declare upfront the technical space they will target.

elements.name: transforms
elements.documentation: Houses all of the transformations supported by assets.

elements.name: transforms::context
elements.documentation:
Context for all assets transformations.

Contains all of the external data required for the transformations
to execute. It's not ideal to have a huge "global" class, with lots
of unrelated state; however, over time, we found that a number of
arguments were being supplied across the call graph, resulting in a
lot of repetitive code. The context gathers together all of these.

elements.documentation: An error occurred whilst applying a transformation.

elements.name: helpers::validation_error
elements.documentation: An error occurred during validation.

elements.name: helpers::indexing_error

elements.name: helpers::resolution_error
elements.documentation: An error occurred while trying to resolve a type.

elements.name: helpers::mapping_error
elements.documentation: An error has occurred while mapping element names.

elements.documentation:
Consistent unit of mapping that can be used to translate a model from one technical
space to another.

Representation of the identifier that can usable as an identifier on all of the

elements.name: meta_model::Container

elements.documentation:

properties related to decorations.

elements.name: meta_model::decoration::licence
elements.documentation: Represents legal licence for software projects.

attributes.name: short_form
attributes.documentation: Short version of the licence, for inclusion in project files.

attributes.name: long_form
attributes.documentation: Long form of the licence text, suitable for generation of LICENCE files.

elements.name: meta_model::decoration::modeline_group

attributes.name: modelines
attributes.documentation: Modelines that make up the group.

elements.name: meta_model::decoration::modeline
elements.documentation:
Groups all the fields representing editor variables for emacs, vi, etc.

A field is a key-value pair (KVP), where name is the first element and its value
the second.

Example: -*- mode: c++; tab-width: 4; indent-tabs-mode: nil; c-basic-offset: 4 -*-

In this particular case, both prefix and postfix are @e -*-; @e mode is the first
field name and its value is @e c++; the KVP separator is @e : and the field
separator is @e ;.

attributes.name: editor
attributes.documentation: The modeline will use the syntax for this editor.

attributes.name: location
attributes.documentation: Where to place the modeline.

attributes.name: fields
attributes.documentation: List of all the parameters in the preamble, in order of appearence.

attributes.name: technical_space
attributes.documentation: Technical space that this modeline targets.

attributes.name: emacs

attributes.name: vi

attributes.name: vim

attributes.name: ex

attributes.name: name

attributes.name: value

elements.documentation: Location in the file to place the modeline.

attributes.name: top
attributes.documentation: Very first line in file.

attributes.name: bottom
attributes.documentation: Very last line in file.

elements.name: meta_model::decoration::generation_marker
elements.documentation:
Properties of the "generation marker" to add to generated files.

These are also known as "location strings".

attributes.name: add_date_time
attributes.documentation:
If true, the location strings will include the date and time of generation.

This is not recomended for models that are generated often as it will trigger
rebuilds for no good reason.

attributes.name: add_dogen_version
attributes.documentation: If true, adds the version of dogen used to generate the code.

attributes.name: add_model_to_text_transform_details
attributes.documentation: If true, adds information about the transform used to generate the file.

attributes.name: add_warning
attributes.documentation: If true, warns users that the file was code-generated.

attributes.name: add_origin_sha1_hash
attributes.documentation: If true, adds the SHA1 hash of the original model to the marker.

attributes.name: message
attributes.documentation: Custom message to add to each generated file.

elements.name: meta_model::variability
elements.documentation:
Houses all of the meta-modeling elements related
to variability.

attributes.name: parents
attributes.documentation: Parents of this profile template.

elements.name: meta_model::variability::feature_template_bundle

attributes.name: feature_templates
attributes.documentation: Set of feature templates associated with this feature template bundle.

attributes.name: generate_static_configuration
attributes.documentation: If true, the code generator will output a class to represent the static configuration.

attributes.name: requires_manual_default_constructor
attributes.documentation:
If true, the code generated for this feature template bundle needs a manually
generated default constructor.

attributes.name: template_kind
attributes.documentation: Kind of template expansion to perform for this feature template.

attributes.name: location
attributes.documentation: Archetype location coordinates for the feature template to expand into.

attributes.name: default_binding_point
attributes.documentation:
Default binding point for all feature templates in this bundle.

The binding point indicates where the feature will bind when instantiated in a
model. If the default binding point is supplied for a bundle, the templates cannot
supply individual binding points. Conversely, if not supplied, they must supply
their individual binding points.

elements.name: meta_model::variability::feature_template
elements.documentation:
Represents a feature template in variability space.

Feature templates are expanded into features within the variability model.

attributes.name: key
attributes.documentation: Identifier of the feature template, as will be seen by the end user.

attributes.name: identifiable_key
attributes.documentation: Post-processed key, suitable for use as an identifier.

attributes.name: unparsed_type
attributes.documentation:
Type of the static configuration field, as read out from original model.

This is the type before mapping and parsing.

attributes.name: mapped_type
attributes.documentation: Unparsed type, after mapping has taken place.

attributes.name: parsed_type
attributes.documentation: Mapped type, after parsing has taken place.

attributes.name: value
attributes.documentation: String representing the default value set on the model.

attributes.name: value_type
attributes.documentation: Type of the value pointed to by the feature.

attributes.name: binding_point
attributes.documentation:
Override binding point for this feature template.

If the default binding point is supplied for a bundle, the templates cannot
supply individual binding points. Conversely, if not supplied, they must supply
their individual binding points.

attributes.name: is_optional
attributes.documentation: If true, the feature generated by the feature template is optional.

attributes.name: requires_optionality
attributes.documentation:
If true, the feature's static configuration will have an optional type.

This is only required if the feature template is optional and has no default value.

elements.name: meta_model::variability::feature_template_initializer
elements.documentation: Responsible for initialising features and feature templates.

attributes.name: feature_template_bundles
attributes.documentation: Names of all the templates that this initialiser will register.

attributes.name: feature_bundles
attributes.documentation: Names of all the features that this initialiser will register.

attributes.name: has_primary_key
attributes.documentation: True if the object has an attribute marked as a primary key, false otherwise.

attributes.name: column_name

attributes.name: is_primary_key
attributes.documentation: If true, this attribute is a primary key for the relation.

attributes.name: is_nullable
attributes.documentation: If true, the attribute can be NULL.

attributes.name: is_composite

elements.documentation: Decoration for this element.

attributes.name: preamble
attributes.documentation:
Preamble for all artefacts created from this element.

The preamble is located at the top of an artefact and includes elements such as a
modeline, licence,  copyrights, etc.

attributes.name: postamble
attributes.documentation:
Postamble for all artefacts created from this element.

The postamble is located at the bottom of an artefact and includes elements such
as a modeline.

Houses all of the meta-modeling elements related

elements.name: meta_model::structural::object
elements.documentation:
Representation of the class notion in the OOP paradigm.

The @e object is equivalent to a meta-class, but we decided against this
name because all elements should also have the prefix meta - after all, assets
is ameta-model. Since the word class cannot be used in c++ to name types, we
decided instead to use the word object.

attributes.name: object_templates

attributes.name: provides_opaqueness

attributes.name: can_be_primitive_underlier
attributes.documentation: If true, this object can be the underlying element of a primitive.

attributes.documentation: Whether to mark a type as final or not.

attributes.name: masd.generalization.parent
attributes.documentation: Name of the parent of the current element.

elements.name: features::origin
elements.documentation: Features related to the origin of the model.

attributes.name: masd.injection.is_proxy_model
attributes.documentation: If true, sets the origin of the model to "proxy model".

elements.name: features::output_technical_space
elements.documentation: Features related to the output technical space.

attributes.name: masd.extraction.output_technical_space
attributes.documentation: Set of output technical spaces that this model targets.

elements.name: features::primitive
elements.documentation: Features related to primitive elements.

attributes.name: masd.primitive.underlying_element
attributes.documentation: Name of the underlying element to use for the primitive.

attributes.name: masd.primitive.is_nullable
attributes.documentation: If true, the primitive can be null.

attributes.name: masd.primitive.use_type_aliasing
attributes.documentation:
If true, use type aliasing to implement the primitive if the technical space supports
it.

elements.name: features::orm
elements.documentation: Features related to ORM support.

attributes.name: masd.orm.database_system
attributes.documentation: Database system to target for ORM support.

attributes.name: masd.orm.table_name
attributes.documentation: Name of the database table for this element.

attributes.name: masd.orm.schema_name
attributes.documentation: Name of the database schema for this modeling element.

attributes.name: masd.orm.is_primary_key
attributes.documentation: If true, this property will be used for the primary key.

attributes.name: masd.orm.column_name
attributes.documentation: Overrides the name of the column name for the database table.

attributes.name: masd.orm.is_nullable
attributes.documentation: If true, the column can be null.

attributes.name: masd.orm.is_composite
attributes.documentation: If true, the primary key is a composite key.

attributes.name: masd.orm.letter_case
attributes.documentation: Determines the casing to use for identifiers.

attributes.name: masd.orm.type_override
attributes.documentation:
Overrides to use for the relational type, for a given database system.

Note: we've set the binding point to "any" as a hack to allow for primitive support.
Should really be "property".

attributes.name: masd.orm.type_mapping
attributes.documentation:
Type maps to create for the relational type, possibly for a given database system.

Note: we've set the binding point to "any" as a hack to allow for primitive support.
Should really be "property".

attributes.name: masd.orm.odb_pragma
attributes.documentation:
Raw ODB pragmas that are applied as-is by the system.

Use these when you need some functionality which is not natively supported by
ORM in Dogen.

elements.name: features::decoration_modeline
elements.documentation: Modeline properties.

attributes.name: masd.decoration.modeline.editor
attributes.documentation: Editor to use in this modeline.

attributes.name: masd.decoration.modeline.location
attributes.documentation: Where to place the modeline.

attributes.name: masd.decoration.modeline.technical_space
attributes.documentation: Technical space targeted by the modeline.

elements.name: features::variability_templates
elements.documentation: Features related to the processing of variability for feature and profile templates.

attributes.name: masd.variability.binding_point
attributes.documentation: Where does this feature bind into.

attributes.name: masd.variability.labels
attributes.documentation: Labels to apply to this profile. These are used for binding, via stereotypes.

attributes.name: masd.variability.value
attributes.documentation:
Value for a facet or profile template.

Value as meta-data should be used only for collections, for single values prefer
the default value field if available.

attributes.name: masd.variability.qualified_name
attributes.documentation:
Qualified name for this feature template.

Should only be supplied for instance templates.

attributes.name: masd.variability.is_optional
attributes.documentation: If true, the feature template provides an optional feature.

elements.name: meta_model::mapping
elements.documentation: Meta-model elements related to mapping domains.

elements.name: meta_model::mapping::extensible_mappable
elements.documentation:
A mappable meta-model element for the general purpose of mapping.

Mappables can be used to create a Platform Independent Model (PIM), which is then
mapped to concrete types to form a Platform Specific Model (PSM). Users can
extend the mappings as required.

attributes.name: destinations
attributes.documentation: All the destinations that this source has been mapped to.

elements.name: features::mapping
elements.documentation: Meta-data related to element mapping.

attributes.name: masd.mapping.target
attributes.documentation: Type that is the source of the mapping.

attributes.name: masd.mapping.destination
attributes.documentation: Type that is the destination of the mapping.

elements.name: meta_model::mapping::fixed_mappable
elements.documentation:
A mappable meta-model element for a special purpose.

At present, the only fixed mappables used by Dogen are related to the mapping of
variability types.

elements.name: meta_model::templating
elements.documentation: Meta-model elements related to templating .

elements.name: meta_model::templating::logic_less_template
elements.documentation:
Represents a logic-less template.

At present the system only supports wale templates.

elements.name: features::variability_bundle
elements.documentation: Features related to the processing of variability for feature bundles.

attributes.name: masd.variability.generate_static_configuration
attributes.documentation: If true, generates a c++ class to contain the configuration at compile time.

attributes.name: masd.variability.archetype_location.kernel
attributes.documentation: Kernel for a facet or profile template.

attributes.name: masd.variability.archetype_location.backend
attributes.documentation: Backend for a facet or profile template.

attributes.name: masd.variability.archetype_location.facet
attributes.documentation: Facet for a facet or profile template.

attributes.name: masd.variability.archetype_location.archetype
attributes.documentation: Archetype for a facet or profile template.

attributes.name: masd.variability.template_kind
attributes.documentation: Template kind for a facet or profile template.

attributes.name: masd.variability.default_binding_point
attributes.documentation: Where does this bundle bind to.

elements.name: meta_model::serialization
elements.documentation:
Houses all of the meta-modeling elements related
to serialisation.

elements.name: meta_model::serialization::type_registrar
elements.documentation:
Responsible for registering types for serialisation purposes.

Certain libraries in certain technical spaces - such as Boost Serialisation, in C++ -
require types that are in an inheritance relationship to be made known to the
serialisation infrastructure in order for the deserialisation of base and derived
types to work. The type registrar is aware of all types with such requirements and
generates the registration code as needed.

attributes.name: leaves
attributes.documentation: List of all concrete classes which are part of an inheritance tree.

attributes.name: registrar_dependencies
attributes.documentation: Registrars on other models this registrar depends on.

elements.name: meta_model::orm::Schemable
elements.documentation: Model element can belong to a relational database schema.

attributes.name: schema_name
attributes.documentation: Name of the database schema in which to place this element.

attributes.name: capitalised_schema_name
attributes.documentation: Schema name with the correct capitalisation.

elements.name: meta_model::orm::Caseable
elements.documentation: The model element supports configuration related to casing.

attributes.name: letter_case
attributes.documentation: What case to use for the database identifiers.

attributes.name: generate_mapping
attributes.documentation: If true, object-relational mapping will be generated for this element.

attributes.name: type_mappings
attributes.documentation: List of mappings of relational database types.

attributes.name: odb_pragmas
attributes.documentation: Pragmas for the ODB ORM backend.

attributes.name: type_overrides
attributes.documentation: Override the default type for this attribute for a given database system.

attributes.name: source_type
attributes.documentation: Type which we intend to map from. Example: TEXT.

attributes.name: destination_type
attributes.documentation: Type we intend to map to. Example: JSONB.

attributes.name: to_source_type
attributes.documentation: Function that converts into the source type.

attributes.name: to_destination_type
attributes.documentation: Function that converts into the destination type.

attributes.name: database
attributes.documentation: Database to which the mapping applies. If none is supplied, it will apply to all.

elements.name: meta_model::visual_studio
elements.documentation:
Houses meta-model elements related to
build systems.

elements.name: meta_model::visual_studio::project
elements.documentation: Represents a Visual Studio project.

attributes.name: type_guid
attributes.documentation: GUID used by Visual Studio to identify projects of this type.

attributes.name: item_groups
attributes.documentation: Set of item groups in the project.

attributes.name: project_name
attributes.documentation: Formatted name of the project.

attributes.name: solutions
attributes.documentation: All solutions in this model.

attributes.name: projects
attributes.documentation: All projects in this model.

elements.name: meta_model::visual_studio::item_group
elements.documentation:
Represents an MSBuild ItemGroup.

Documented as follows: Contains a set of user-defined Item elements. Every item
used in a MSBuild project must be specified as a child of an ItemGroup element.

attributes.name: items
attributes.documentation: Set of MSBuild Items that make up this ItemGroup.

elements.name: meta_model::visual_studio::item
elements.documentation:
Represents an MSBuild Item, used in Visual Studio projects.

Documentation:  Contains a user-defined item and its metadata. Every item that is
used in a MSBuild project must be specified as a child of an ItemGroup element.

attributes.name: name
attributes.documentation:
Name of the item, such as "Compile", "CompileCl", etc.

Maps to a well known MSBuild target.

attributes.name: include
attributes.documentation: Name of the file to include.

attributes.name: project_persistence_blocks
attributes.documentation: Set of project persistence blocks in this solution.

attributes.name: name
attributes.documentation: Name of the project.

attributes.name: relative_path
attributes.documentation: Relative path to the project file.

attributes.name: type_guid
attributes.documentation: GUID used by Visual Studio to identify projects of this type.

attributes.name: guid
attributes.documentation: GUID that uniquely identifies this element.

elements.name: meta_model::structural::entry_point
elements.documentation: Represents an entry point to a binary.

elements.name: meta_model::build
elements.documentation:
Houses all of the meta-modeling elements related
to building, which don't have their own containing
namespace.

elements.name: meta_model::build::cmakelists
elements.documentation: Represents build CMakeLists files.

elements.name: meta_model::structural::assistant
elements.documentation: General type to provide helpers.

elements.name: meta_model::variability::feature_bundle

attributes.name: features
attributes.documentation: Set of features associated with this feature bundle.

attributes.name: generate_static_configuration
attributes.documentation: If true, the code generator will output a class to represent the static configuration.

attributes.name: requires_manual_default_constructor
attributes.documentation:
If true, the code generated for this feature bundle needs a manually generated
default constructor.

attributes.name: location
attributes.documentation: Archetype location coordinates for the feature.

attributes.name: default_binding_point
attributes.documentation:
Default binding point for all features in this bundle.

The binding point indicates where the feature will bind when instantiated in a
model. If the default binding point is supplied for a bundle, the templates cannot
supply individual binding points. Conversely, if not supplied, they must supply
their individual binding points.

elements.name: meta_model::variability::feature
elements.documentation: Represents a feature in variability space.

attributes.name: key
attributes.documentation: Identifier of the feature, as will be seen by the end user.

attributes.name: identifiable_key
attributes.documentation: Post-processed key, suitable for use as an identifier.

attributes.name: unparsed_type
attributes.documentation:
Type of the static configuration field, as read out from original model.

This is the type before mapping and parsing.

attributes.name: mapped_type
attributes.documentation: Unparsed type, after mapping has taken place.

attributes.name: parsed_type
attributes.documentation: Mapped type, after parsing has taken place.

attributes.name: value
attributes.documentation: String representing the default value set on the model.

attributes.name: value_type
attributes.documentation: Type of the value pointed to by the feature.

attributes.name: binding_point
attributes.documentation:
Override binding point for this feature.

If the default binding point is supplied for a bundle, the features cannot
supply individual binding points. Conversely, if not supplied, they must supply
their individual binding points.

attributes.name: is_optional
attributes.documentation: If true, the feature generated by the feature template is optional.

attributes.name: requires_optionality
attributes.documentation:
If true, the feature's static configuration will have an optional type.

This is only required if the feature template is optional and has no default value.
